WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.800
[Amit Varma]: What do the 1990s mean to you? The answer, of course, depends on context. Where you were

00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:15.900
[Amit Varma]: during those years, what your experiences were like at the time, the kind of music and

00:00:15.900 --> 00:00:20.120
[Amit Varma]: books and films you consumed, and some of you may not even have been born then. My last

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:24.520
[Amit Varma]: episode where J. Arjun Singh and Subrat Mohanty was about cinema, and though none of us would

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:29.520
[Amit Varma]: call the 90s our favourite decade in terms of films, it was pleasant enough. Kieslowski,

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:34.680
[Amit Varma]: Tarantino, David Dhawan, what's not to like? But think about the 1990s from the point of

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:40.840
[Amit Varma]: view of a Kashmiri child growing up in Kashmir in a time of constant curfew, occasional raids,

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:45.240
[Amit Varma]: army bunkers in residential neighbourhoods, and the fear, every time a loved one left

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:49.960
[Amit Varma]: home, that they may not return. For you had seen this before, and death was both normal

00:00:49.960 --> 00:00:54.240
[Amit Varma]: and normalised. How do you grow up in a world like that? How do you process it and make

00:00:54.240 --> 00:01:00.880
[Amit Varma]: sense of it? What do the 1990s mean to you?

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:06.040
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:13.800
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:17.920
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Farah Bashir, who studied psychology

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:22.400
[Amit Varma]: in college, worked as a photojournalist for Reuters, and then chose to walk away from

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:27.960
[Amit Varma]: that life and try and write about her past. Farah grew up in Kashmir in the 1990s, took

00:01:27.960 --> 00:01:32.360
[Amit Varma]: years to come to terms with that childhood, and has now brought it to us in a deeply moving

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:37.080
[Amit Varma]: book called Rumours of Spring. Rumours of Spring is narrated from the point of view

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:41.800
[Amit Varma]: of the adolescent Farah before she comes to adulthood and gains the frames to make sense

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:47.400
[Amit Varma]: of that world. It's impressionistic and detailed, and gives us such a clear view of that young

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:52.400
[Amit Varma]: girl's interior life, which mirrors both the starkness and turmoil of her exterior

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:56.520
[Amit Varma]: world. It's a powerful book that has stayed with me after I read it, and I was delighted

00:01:56.520 --> 00:02:01.280
[Amit Varma]: to have Farah on this show to talk about her experiences as a child in Kashmir, and about

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:06.320
[Amit Varma]: the experience of reliving that childhood and writing this book. Before we begin our

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:10.360
[Amit Varma]: conversation though, let's go to a unique kind of commercial break, Capital Gyan by

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:14.320
[Amit Varma]: Deepak Chinoy. This is like a show within a commercial from the kind sponsors of this

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:18.880
[Amit Varma]: episode, Capital Mind. And today's show within a commercial, is like a commercial

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:23.320
[Amit Varma]: for this show, which is too meta for me, but what to do? Deepak is like that only.

